Teacher admits shooting girlfriend during 911 call
A voice only slightly shivering college teacher Shannon Lamb tells police during a 911 call that he shot his girlfriend and that officers need to come to their house.
Lamb stressed that her "golden dog" is alive and probably upset, as well as saying that contact information for the dead woman's next of kin can be found on her phone.
Inside the house, officers found Amy Prentiss' body and a handwritten note on the side of the notebook: "I'm so sorry I wish I could take this back I loved Amy and she's the only woman who ever loved me," said the letter, which experts say was signed by Lamb.
There was nothing to suggest that Lamb, who taught two online classes at Delta State University in Cleveland, Minnesota, had already traveled nearly 500 kilometers to the school's campus, where police believe he shot and killed a well-liked history teacher, Ethan Schmidt, on the doorstep of his study.
Delta State University Police Chief Lynn Buford said university officials heard gunfire at 10:18 a.m.
He said Lamb made the fatal 911 call some time after that.
By the end of the day, the death toll rose by one more: Lamb committed suicide as police surrounded the sound.
Authorities were still trying to determine Lamb's motive a day after students and staff had to hide behind locked doors because of the school shooting.
Investigators on both sides of the state have released information that students and staff described Lamb as a gifted teacher who, however, potentially had problems.
Students said they had been waiting for her classes.
Police in the town where Prentiss died, Gautier, say Lamb had no violent past or criminal record.
Schmidt himself had included Lamb in a book he wrote thanking the "awesome people" with whom he shared his academic life.
Both taught at the Department of Social Sciences and History, which has a total of 17 staff members, and many of the students attended each man's classes.
On the other hand, there were some signs of trouble.
A student named Brandon Beavers praised Lamb, but said he also seemed nervous and uneasy, "as if something was off."
Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamb told him he was under a lot of stress at the end of the 2014-15 school year.
Lamb had previously asked for medical leave from Delta State University, saying he had some sort of health issue.
This year, he taught only two online courses.
Recent changes in the university's hiring principles meant that while Lamb had worked hard for his doctorate, it did not guarantee him automatic career advancement and an assistant professorship.
University President William LaForge said there was no conflict of any kind between Lamb and Schmidt to his knowledge, but that "clearly there was something on Lamb's mind."
These are questions Lamb can no longer answer.
After Lamb fled the campus, police were able to track him down as he moved back to Mississippi from the state of Arkansas.
Before he could be arrested, Lamb shot himself with a .38-caliber pistol in the backyard of a house about a mile and a half south of his parents' house in the Greenville suburb of Mississippi, said Methel Johnson, the Washington County coroner.
Lamb's car was still running in the driveway.
It was not immediately clear why Lamb went to this particular house, though Johnson said he believes Lamb knew the people who live there.
Lamb grew up in the area.
Lamb began working at the university in 2009 and taught geography and education. The university has 3500 students and is located in a city with about 12,000 residents.
Lamb completed his Ph.D. in education in the spring.
One of Lamb's old friends described him as intelligent, charismatic and funny.
Carla Hairston said she was 15 and Lamb was 20 when they met through mutual friends.
Hairston and his friends were in high school, and Lamb was a funny, older guy who tried for many years to teach Hairston how to play guitar.
He was quite a charmer in those days.
All the girls were molten wax when she was there, said Hairston, now 40, who lives in the Jackson suburb of Brandon.
Lamb and Prentiss had apparently been dating for a while.
In a 911 call, Lamb said he killed his wife, but there is no evidence whatsoever of their marriage.
They had a dog named Lightning who lived with them in a riverfront brick house in Gautier.
Police said the dog was fine.
Prentiss' former husband, Shawn O'Steen, said they divorced 15 years ago but remained friends. They now have a 19-year-old daughter.
"She's really upset," O'Steen described her daughter.
He was her mother's best friend.
Mr O'Steen said he had not met Lamb but had heard from his daughter Abigail that Lamb was interested in music and played the blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when Lamb and Abigail were both performing at a summer market three years ago.
Later, they played some gigs together.
O'Steen said her daughter makes and sings her own music.
Prentiss was a nurse who worked for a variety of online companies.
Mike Shaffer, a bartender and occasional entertainment organizer at The Julep Room, a shady bar near Gautier, says he last saw Lamb and Prentiss on the night of Sept. 5, after Lamb finished his guitar and harmonica recital for a sparse audience.
Nothing seemed wrong.
"Just a happy couple," he said.
We messed around and threw slurs at each other.
So they were both quite clever.
Schmidt, the dead teacher, ran a seminary program for first-year students and specialized in Indians and colonial history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English teacher at the school.
Schmidt was married with three young children.
He studied at Emporia State University in Kansas, as well as being the president of his fraternity and student government.
On Tuesday night, a candlelight devotion was held on the Delta State campus in Cleveland with about 900 people attending, including teaching and other staff, students and community members.
Schmidt's wife, Liz, and brother, Jeff Schmidt, also attended the Mass, during which the university choir sang the songs Bright Morning Star and Amazing Grace.
Teaching will resume on Wednesday.
"We're trying to get our students to come back," LaForge said.
The crisis is over.
Now is the time for recovery.
Amy and Rogelio Solis reported from Cleveland, Mississippi.
Associated Press writer Emily Wagster Pettus in Greenville, Mississippi, and Rebecca Santana in New Orleans contributed to this report.
