8 poll results that show Donald Trump is serious
Some have tried to brand him as a wind-up banner.
Others just think he's a joke.
Some are waiting for collapse.
While some Republicans have tried to gridlock Donald Trump out of the top spot in endorsement polls, it hasn't (yet) been successful.
In 10 of the last 11 national polls, Donald Trump has been leading by double digits, and some have begun to seriously consider what this means for the real estate king's nomination chances.
Of course, the election season is still in its early stages.
Those results don't yet mean Trump is likely to become the Republican nominee.
Commentators point out that at this point in 2011, Rick Perry was losing his lead to the rising Herman Cain, neither of whom got behind any states in the nominating process.
There are also many reasons why he would have problems in a general election.
But outside groups, including Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the conservative economic organization Club for Growth, have noted Trump's resilience and begun using their funds to bring him down.
The following recent poll results suggest that the real estate king isn't just a passing phase:
Trump's popularity numbers have done an about-face.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, Monmouth University endorsement polls showed that only two Republicans in 10 welcomed the real estate king.
By mid-July, the figure was 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, the figure was 52 per cent.
Currently, six in 10 Republicans view Donald Trump favorably.
About three in 10 say they have a negative view.
Those numbers hold true in the first primary states, too.
In an endorsement poll conducted by Quinnipiac University in Iowa last week, 60 percent of Republicans said they had a favorable view of Trump.
Two-thirds of Republican voters would be satisfied if Trump were to become the nominee.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would either be "excited" or "satisfied" if Trump were the nominee.
Only two in 10 said they would be "shocked" if he became a candidate.
Only Ben Carson generates roughly the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent "excited" vs. Trump's 40 percent).
The next most exciting?
Marco Rubio at just 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters would be "disgruntled" or "shocked" if establishment favorite Jeb Bush became the nominee.
Trump's fiery temper is not a problem for most Republicans.
While Donald Trump has been widely criticized for his bombastic speeches and insults, according to Monday's ABC News/Washington Post poll, 52 percent of Republican-leaning voters at the national level think the real estate king has the character befitting a president.
According to last week's Quinnipiac poll, in the state of Iowa, which is hosting the first convention, the figure is the same: 52 percent of Republicans think Trump has the character befitting a leader.
But according to an ABC/Post poll, 44 percent think his character isn't suited to serving as president, and nearly six in 10 think his character doesn't belong in the White House.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When Republican voters think like commentators, they take the view that Trump is the real alternative.
According to a CNN/ORC poll, four in 10 thought Trump was the most likely choice when asked who was most likely to be nominated for the Republican nomination.
As recently as the end of July, four in 10 supported Jeb Bush.
Disclosure of the data: Republican Party voters have not always had access to the brightest possible crystal ball.
At this time last election season, four in 10 Republicans thought Rick Perry would be nominated, and only 28 percent supported the eventual nominee, Mitt Romney.
Either way, this shows that the majority of Republican voters think the Trump campaign is credible.
Even if Republicans line up to endorse another candidate, Trump would still win nearly every one.
Some commentators have pointed out that the splintered field likely has contributed to Trump's leadership, as anti-Trump support is split among numerous other candidates.
However, a poll conducted by Monmouth University in early September showed that in a hypothetical bilateral race between Trump and almost every other Republican candidate, Trump receives majority support in almost all cases.
He leads Carly Fiorina by 13 points, Marco Rubio by 14 points, Walker by 15, Jeb Bush by 19 and Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie each by 33 points.
He's tied for the lead with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate to beat Trump?
If they were pitted against each other, Ben Carson would beat businessman Trump by a big 18 points.
A majority of Donald Trump’s supporters say they’ve made a decision.
A new CBS/NYT poll from Tuesday shows that just over half of pro-Trump voters have decided who their vote will go to.
Of course, the situation can change, and no one can say with absolute certainty that they will never change their mind.
Forty-six percent said they could potentially switch candidates.
Either way, Trump's biggest rival right now is another unlikely winner, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but those voters who said they made the decision are twice as likely to side with Trump.
Six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Ever since Donald Trump two months ago called Mexican immigrants "rapists" in his campaign launch speech, immigration has been at the center of the 2016 debate.
Some worry that Trump's largess will drive Latino voters further away from the Republican Party and hurt rebranding efforts.
According to a new ABC/Post poll released Monday, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
So it seems that as long as immigration is at the heart of things, so is Donald Trump.
Frustration with the government has reached a new peak.
Support for Donald Trump and Ben Carson now covers about half of Republican voters, largely due to their position outside of politics.
Six in 10 Republicans said in Monday's ABC/Post poll that they would rather choose a person outside of politics than one with government experience.
They are also angry at the federal government.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll from Iowa two weeks ago showed that three in four Iowa Republicans are frustrated with Republicans in Congress: 54 percent are "disgruntled" and 21 percent are "really angry."
Jeremy Corbyn's first appearance at Prime Minister's Question Time
Corbyn's first appearance on Question Time has been eagerly awaited since his election
Jeremy Corbyn, the new Labour leader, will face David Cameron for the first time at Prime Minister's Question Time.
Mr Corbyn rises to ask the first of his six questions shortly after midday, and is likely to be watched closely by both the media and Labour MPs for his performance.
Corbyn has called for "less theatre and more facts" at this weekly show.
He has also said he could leave some of the opportunities to his colleagues.
This encounter will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corbyn's leadership since he was appointed to the shadow cabinet and addressed the annual meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand quietly during the national anthem at Tuesday's commemoration service for the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain air war has drawn criticism from Conservative MPs and featured in a number of front-page stories.
Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he "stood respectfully silent" and that he recognises "the bravery of the Royal Air Force in the Great British Air War."
Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet member, Owen Smith, stated to BBC Two's Newsnight programme that he would have urged the Labour leader to sing the national anthem despite his belief that the royal house should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to be involved in Corbyn's inner circle, citing differences on economic, defence and foreign affairs. Originally less than a sixth of the parliamentary party supported him as leader.
BBC policy correspondent Robin Brant says policy differences over the party's position in the European Union as well as the government's aid cap have also "piled up" within the Labour Party since Mr Corbyn was appointed.
Speaking at a meeting of the Confederation of Trade Unions, Mr Corbyn said Labour would bring forward an amendment that would remove the entire cap.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow government work and pensions secretary, stated that the party was "quite clear" that they were merely opposing the government's plans to lower the ceiling from £26,000 to £23,0000.
Mr Corbyn will become the fifth Labour leader David Cameron has faced in the past decade, when he has been leader of the Conservative Party.
The Labour leader has promised a new approach to policy and now reports that he has "crowdsourced" ideas into questions for the prime minister, and received more than 30,000 proposals.
Mr Corbyn, the MP for the Islington North area, has said that the nature of the Prime Minister's Question Time is too confrontational and that he intends to refrain from both witty diction and barbs, promising instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality as well as the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the shadow cabinet economic secretary, deputises for him during Question Time when Mr Corbyn does not attend - for example, when Mr Cameron is abroad.
Mr Corbyn has also suggested that other colleagues could also sometimes be allowed to speak and has said he approached the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, about the issue.
When Mr Cameron took over in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the kind of political theatre often associated with Prime Minister's Question Time, but he was later forced to admit he had failed.
Since they began being televised in 1990, the Prime Minister's Question Time has been an important measure of the leader's judgment, his control of the Commons, as well as his standing with other MPs, although critics have criticised the Question Hours for becoming little more than a travesty calling for far-reaching reforms.
