Pound set to rise as UK wage growth accelerates
The value of the pound jumped upwards after the numbers showed a rise in UK pay growth, and at the same time the FTSE 100 index rose with bidding target SABMiller.
Between May and July UK wages, excluding bonuses, rose by 2.9 per cent compared with the same time last year.
The pace of growth was the fastest since 2009 and was seen as bringing with it estimates of rising rates.
The pound rose more than 1 per cent against the dollar to $1.5505, and 0.84 per cent against the euro to €1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed up 1.49 per cent at 6229.21.
SABMiller was the most distinctive stock in the market and rose 20 per cent after rival AB InBev approached it with an offer.
The deal would combine two of the world's largest brewers and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry's stock rose 0.9 per cent after encouraging news from rival luxury goods group Richmont.
Not only were Richemont's latest sales figures better than expected, they also showed that sales in China - a key market for Burberry - had started to grow again.
Glencore shares rose 5 per cent after the mining giant said it had raised $2.5bn by issuing shares as part of its debt-cutting strategy.
Shares in Mondi, the packaging and paper group, were among the biggest fallers on the index at 4.3 per cent after Goldman Sachs changed its recommendation on the company to "sell."
JD Sports rose 3.1 per cent after the sportswear company disclosed information on its half-year pre-tax profits: an 83 per cent rise to £46.6 million.
JD Sports chief says higher wages could hurt expansion
Peter Cowgill, the head of JD Sports, says that if the minimum wage for workers in the UK is increased, it could mean that "potential consumers will have more buying power."
However, this purchasing power is unlikely to exceed the higher labor costs to the company, Cowgill notes.
The cost might fall on the company's expansion plans, he added, which would mean fewer additional jobs.
Metcash launches grassroots campaign against encroachment on Aldi's sector
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from attack by Aldi in South and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to defend the market share of IGA traders in South and Western Australia ahead of Aldi's $700 million attack.
Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centres as well as its first store early next year in South and Western Australia, with up to 120 stores on the way. Meanwhile, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food brokers and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing, as well as events such as the Adelaide show.
Traders and purveyors of IGA have jumped in, with brands such as Simmo's, the ice cream maker from Dunsborough, offering tastings at IGA stores, and shop owners selling cut-price tickets to Australian football matches to their regular customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details of its defensive strategy on September 29, when this wholesaler of food, alcohol and hardware holds its annual Investor Strategy Day.
There is a lot at stake as South and Western Australia together account for almost 30 per cent of the area of Metcash's IGA stores, with higher profit margins than Metcash's eastern states IGA network.
Shoppers in South and Western Australia are notoriously parochial, with IGA retailers holding a much higher market share than those in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: more than 30 per cent in the south and 24 per cent in the west compared with 14 per cent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will grab about 5 per cent of the food market in the two states within 12 months of opening the first stores. Turnover will come from all operators, but mainly independent retailers.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA dealers could lose $360 million in sales each year and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in the south and 30 in the west next year, generating turnovers of $500m and $600m respectively in these areas.
The loss of food and food sales and volumes at Metcash's high fixed expenses base could cost Metcash about $13 million in operating profit losses before interest and taxes, Kierath said.
Meanwhile, Metcash is losing market share in eastern states mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent Roy Morgan study found that IGA customers were the most loyal of all.
Morgan Stanley believes that Metcash's food and food sales will fall 3.8 per cent in 2016; 4.1 per cent in 2017 and 2.1 per cent in 2018, such that its market share will fall from 14 per cent in 2015 to 10.3 per cent in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, manager of a leading investment fund and founder of Magellan Financial Group, said at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could "very possibly lose out in a decade."
Metcash has declined to respond publicly to Douglass' comments.
However, it is understood a member of the Metcash board would have contacted Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen since 2010 from 18 per cent to 14 per cent, and revenues from Metcash's food and food business, which brokers products to around 1200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 per cent since 2012. This reflects reduced debt financing for operations as sales and margins come under pressure.
However, the wholesaler is holding its own, and has invested more than $150 million each year in reducing the prices of hundreds of products to the same level as Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA retailers refurbish stores by adding faster-growing fresh food, as well as bringing a better range of private-label products to market.
Metcash chief executive Ian Morrice says falling prices and improving stores have added to the appeal, and he hopes the wholesaler will return to the path of increasing profits in 2017, for the first time in four years.
Australian Tennis Association president Steve Healy backs Thanasi Kokkinakis
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves credit rather than criticism for his behaviour
Thanasi Kokkinakis has had to suffer as a bystander in the recent storm that has raged around her friend Nick Kyrgios. She deserves credit rather than criticism for her own behaviour, notes Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy.
A younger member of the talented duo dubbed "Special Ks," Kokkinakis was involuntarily drawn into the public eye over an incident in which Kyrgios annoyed Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
Soon after, in a fiery qualifying match in Cincinnati, the head judge twice had to separate Kokkinakis and his opponent, Ryan Harrison, when Harrison declared, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should beat that brat."
Although Kokkinakis was last seen smashing his racket after cramp marred his potential victory over Richard Gasquet at the US Open, Healy has been a staunch defender of Kokkinakis.
Right now, the youngster is in Glasgow competing with Sam Groth for the second spot in doubles with Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Britain.
"I feel pretty strongly that Thanasi has just been dragged into the fray," Healy said.
He broke his racket when he lost because of cramp at the U.S. Open, but he's not the first player to break his racket when he's frustrated, and I know Thanas well enough to know he's not proud of that.
But he has behaved superbly, also in quite provocative situations at the US Open with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves praise.
He's got a great team around him, he's got a great family around him, and I think he's been treated a little bit harshly.
He's very mature for 19, he works hard, fits in with the squad and so on, and he's never had a problem with other players. He's appreciated in the dressing room, he trains solidly, is in good form and is quite a calm and mature young man, and as far as I'm concerned he should be judged on his merits.
Healy has also supported the decision not to include Kyrgios in the all-important games starting on Friday, describing this "joint decision" as a good-for-all solution, but still supporting the Canberran's return to the team's regular fixtures.
