This is what happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates
There will be a rate hike, and the market for rising rates will crash, bond yields will rise and the economy will fall into recession.
Here's what we know.
What we don’t know is how long it will take or how long it will take.
The past provides little help in terms of timing, in terms of the economy specifically.
Since the first drawdown, the recession has sometimes taken as little as 11 months, while sometimes as long as 86 months.
The US Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates has often, though not always, been a defining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That's why U.S. Federal Reserve officials have been so vigorous in stressing that investors should focus on that, not because interest rates are starting to be raised, but mainly on the trajectory of the time it takes for the situation to normalize.
Indeed, there are several variables in the equation.
In the end, however, market participants can see that all the fuss about rate hikes has been overdone.
"The central bank's first post-global economic crisis increase will inevitably be interpreted in some quarters as the end of the 'cheap money' era," said Julian Jessop, chief global economics specialist at Capital Economics, in a note to clients.
Instead, we do not expect that the gradual return of US interest rates to normal, albeit still low, levels will be the kind of cataclysmic shock that many seem to fear.
But that doesn't mean it won't have an impact.
Below is a look at how some aspects of the economy will react based on past developments:
As the market has seen over the past month or so, waiting for an interest rate hike can make the situation volatile.
Once the increase becomes a fact, the effect will not be quite so dramatic after all.
"It appears that capital yields tend to stagnate for 12 to 24 months after the first increase, again possibly reflecting a lag in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent survey of what happens after the central bank's increase.
Specifically, over the past 35 years or so the market is generally in a strong uptrend of about 14 per cent as we approach an increase, 250 days after that the situation is fairly flat (an average uptrend of 2.6 per cent), and normality has been reached after 500 days with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4 per cent, according to a recent analysis by Bob Doll, chief equity strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, published in Barron's magazine.
According to Deutsche Bank, the impact on equities tends to be clearer at a later stage of the raising cycle when yields start to fall.
Recessions are part of the economy, but rate hikes often contribute to their arrival.
In the current situation, the central bank is facing certain challenges, previously unaddressed, that could precipitate a recession.
Such is especially the case with gross domestic product, which will come closest to its all-time low before the central bank raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 withdrawals since 1950, nominal annual GDP has only twice been below 4.5 per cent.
While the rate was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it will stick, after advancing 1.5 percent in the third quarter, according to the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economic environment can be risky and raises the question of "whether this time will be different," Deutsche Bank noted.
Market participants have been braced for a Federal Reserve increase throughout the year, and all are looking forward to this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends Thursday.
While many strategists and financial experts believe the committee can approve an increase at this meeting, futures trading anticipates only a 25 percent probability.
"Our research shows that since 1950, all cycles of increases have so far occurred in supercycles of increasing leverage, where GDP has passed its pre-recession peaks very quickly after stimulus has begun," the report says.
By contrast, we have now seen an exceptionally slow recovery from the recession, which has been the worst of the observation period.
In the current cycle, the central bank has waited by far the longest since the last recession ended: the record has been 35 months, and now the 74th month is already under way.
Fixed yields have also been volatile as the market waits for a rate hike, with the model somewhat reminiscent of observations on capital.
The main difference is that as the central bank changes its policy stance, its effects will be seen more quickly in bonds than in equities.
There seems to be an immediate change in the direction of bond yields at the first increase/cut of the cycle.
At the end of the raising cycle, the yield on the bonds will fall immediately," Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe that raising interest rates will cause longer-term and shorter-term bond yields to converge, thereby flattening the yield curve.
High-yield bonds often perform better in such a situation, though "we're still cautious about looking for yield," noted Schwab fixed-income analyst Kathy Jones in one analysis.
Remarkably, Jones believes the market has already adjusted to the central bank's policy expectations.
"Beyond the strength of the dollar and falling inflation expectations, there are several signs that the market has adjusted to the outlook for tighter monetary policy," he wrote.
Short-term interest rates are high, the yield curve is more flat, credit spreads have increased and volatility has increased - all of which are characteristic of markets at times when the central bank has tightened its stance.
Generally speaking, companies whose business is mainly based in the United States win when interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinationals with high levels of debt perform worse when the rising value of the dollar makes their products more expensive on the global market and their debt becomes more expensive than what they have financing.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks in general are more profitable in the three months following the first rate hike," said Goldman Sachs analysts in a report to clients.
Firms with strong turnover outpaced those with weak turnover after increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of five percentage points.
Companies with high return on capital and low volatility shares performed better than lower-quality companies, with an average of 4 (percentage points) for the former and 3 (percentage points) for the latter.
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Those companies with a lot of variable-rate debt stand to lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of stock market speculation, consumers, too, have the opportunity to benefit from a rise in the value of the dollar.
Savers can also turn a profit with higher returns, although experts disagree on how quickly the impact will be felt.
