Surely David Cameron knows the Lorax better than this?
Every parent soon learns one thing: If your child loves a book, it won’t be long before he or she learns it almost by heart.
Unless, of course, you're David Cameron.
When the holiday childcare service asked the Prime Minister about his favourite children's book, he chose Dr Seuss's The Lorax, an environmentalist story published in 1971.
It was a tricky choice, Cameron writes in a post on the SuperCamps company website, and continues: "Funny, moving, creative and contains a strong message. I enjoy reading this book to my children because it always seems to have a picture or message we haven't seen before."
All of this is true, but the next paragraph, in which Cameron presumably describes the book's plot, is a summary of the 2012 film version, in which new characters and details had been added to fill in the fairly short original text.
"In the walled city of Tarville, where all nature has disappeared and even the air is a commodity, Ted the boy hopes to win the heart of the girl of his dreams by fulfilling Audrey's wish to see a real tree," the text says, describing a love story not written by Dr Seuss, whose real name is Theodor Seuss Geisel, who died in 1991.
If this isn't suspicious enough yet, Cameron's text sounds in places like it was taken from a plot summary of a Lorax film found on the Internet Movie Database website, which begins as follows: "In the walled city of Tarville, where everything is artificial and even the air is a commodity, son Ted hopes to win the heart of the Audrey girl of his dreams."
Given that Cameron is a publicly active parent, it seems unlikely that he would be so unfamiliar with the book's plot. In it, a young, nameless boy hears how the local nature has been destroyed by the greedy, tree-hugging and need-weaving Kerskanen, ignoring the short, moustachioed creature that gave the story its name, Lorax, who "speaks for the trees."
Such a relatively invisible PR task is probably outsourced to an assistant who apparently has never read a book 20 times in a row to a child.
A spokesman for the Prime Minister said the text must have come from Mr Cameron's constituency office.
SuperCamps confirmed that the text was received from Mr Cameron's staff but did not comment further at the time.
