Experts criticise Public Health England's e-cigarette review
Researchers have said the state-funded agency's claim that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than traditional ones was prompted by a meeting of 12 people, some with ties to the tobacco industry.
Experts writing for the British Medical Journal (BMJ) joined the Lancet in criticising the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
PHE published this "milestone" report last month, describing it as a "comprehensive review of the evidence."
However, several scientists have questioned the data's durability and pointed to links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
The medical journal Lancet published an editorial last month attacking the "exceptionally shaky bottom line" of PHE's main conclusion.
Two other researchers writing in the BMJ have wondered whether the claims were "built on rock or sand."
Martin McKee, professor of European public health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, professor of clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, say: "The main principle of public health is that policies must be based on proven effectiveness."
They say the public's expectation that PHE's claim "the current best estimate is that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than traditional cigarettes" is based on a detailed assessment and modelling of the evidence.
In fact, it comes from a single meeting of 12 people who developed a multi-criteria decision analysis (MCDA) model to synthesize their opinions on harms associated with various nicotine-containing products, and the results of this meeting were summarized in a study.
Mr McKee and Mr Capewell say one of the sponsors of the meeting was the company name EuroSwiss Health, whose chief executive is reported to have previously received funding from Bristish American Tobacco for an independent investigation.
He also backed BAT's public health mandate in the sustainability report, they say.
One of the 12 people at the meeting reported receiving funding from the e-cigarette maker, but not the funding he reportedly received in the past from tobacco company Philip Morris International, they add.
The criteria for selecting panel members are not disclosed, but the panel includes several well-known supporters of e-cigarettes, some of whom also say in the study that they have received funding from the industry.
Others present are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
The meeting was also attended by PHE's director of tobacco.
The study produced by the group "vastly acknowledges" that there is a lack of "undisputed evidence regarding harm in the vast majority of products and in the vast majority of criteria," McKee and Capewell write.
However, none of these links or restrictions are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell say PHE's claims that "so far there is no evidence that e-cigarettes act as a route to smoking in children or non-smokers" are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of health and wellbeing at PHE, says claims made in the BMJ have been answered in the past.
He says: "E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking."
Half of those who smoke for life die from their addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks posed by e-cigarettes are relatively small, but we must continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what the evidence shows and what it does not, particularly when there is so much public misinformation about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Almost 80,000 people die each year from smoking-related illness and smoking costs the NHS £2bn each year.
By explaining the current evidence - that is, while e-cigarettes are not risk-free, their harms are only a fraction of the harms of conventional tobacco - we are fulfilling our national responsibilities.
