'Sound genetics' allows brain cells to be controlled by sound waves
The video shows the nematodes changing direction as soon as they are hit by the sound impulse.
Scientists have bred worms with genetically engineered neural systems so they can be controlled by sound wave bursts.
The tiny nematodes change direction as soon as they are hit by a sonic impulse too high for the human ear to hear.
The impulses work by switching on genetically engineered motion neurons with membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Related: Scientists Read and Write Brain Activity With Light
The researchers said the worms demonstrate the functionality of a new method, dubbed voice genetics. In it, ultrasound can be used to activate specific brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method may one day replace deep-brain stimulation. It is an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are conducted into people's brains to treat Parkinson's disease.
Nematodes do not normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when they were surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles amplified ultrasound waves, which then travel inside the worms.
The amplified ultrasound waves affect the TRP-4 ion channels, structures that are present in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
To make ultrasonic nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani used ultrasound on the modified worms, the microbubbles amplified sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they turn on the modified motion neurons.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn nerve cells on and off using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says there may be some advantages to using sonogenetics over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which must be sent along an optical fiber to a desired point inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through tissue unimpeded, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic virus, it may be possible to cause the targeted human nerve cells to momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
