Psychologist advises: Here's how to tell kids about refugees
In recent days, many parents have had to think about how to inform their children about the situation of refugees trying to reach Europe.
Or is it worth telling at all?
There is no need to force the issue, advises SPR crisis team member, psychologist Ferdinand Garoff.
Younger children should be protected and not, for example, let them watch the news alone.
Young children are not always able to understand what they are seeing, and it can stick in the mind and become distressing, she says.
However, if a child has come across television news footage of refugees or heard about it elsewhere, it is worth bringing it up.
It is a good idea to discuss the child’s starting points and listen carefully to what he or she asks.
A child’s fears can be surprising.
They're not necessarily the ones a parent imagines she's afraid of.
There is no point in intimidating a child, even if you are distressed and frightened.
Younger children closely monitor the behavior of their parents.
If the parents themselves remain calm during the conversation, the child will feel safe as well.
Older children are more likely to come across conversations about refugees at school, with friends or online.
It is good for parents to bring up the matter with them if the child is thinking about it.
The fact is that not everyone in the world is doing well.
Together with the children, parents can consider how this will be viewed in our family.
After all, do we think that the world is a safe place or a safe place?
Parents may also have different educational perspectives - some may want to protect their children from anxiety where possible.
On the other hand: If the family also talks about difficult issues, the child will get a model for how to deal with the difficulties that come up in life.
This may be useful to him in the future.
