US Federal Reserve policymakers will sit around a huge mahogany table for two days this week in a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of the central bank's ornate, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the shoulders of the Federal Reserve: They must maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
Since the Great Depression, however, central bank leaders have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: economic stability.
It is this third requirement that may be the decisive factor in the decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so tight that it cannot even be predicted. The decision on whether the US economy is ready to be weaned off the record stimulus brought on by the near-zero short-term interest rates since late 2008 .
While most of the data shows the economy is growing solidly, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made central bank officials, who are already wary in advance, even more jumpy, in terms of increasing volatility. There are fears about the impact if the federal funds rate were raised by even a percentage point quarter.
"Understandably, the labor market and inflation are the first and most important issues to watch," notes Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial specialist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I believe that if they are looking for justification for interest rate resetting, increased uncertainty in world markets is a valid enough basis to still wait," he says.
There has been no agreement on the central bank's decision, which is already generating jitters about the economy.
According to a recent Bloomberg survey, about half of economic experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
Financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the drawdown, as a key indicator suggests the chance of growth is only around 30 per cent.
This suggests a fall in securities markets should the central bank raise the level, unless policymakers then manage to soften the blow by promising that the next drawdown won't happen any time soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to 16,599.85 for the new figure.
The recovery was brought on by the expectation that the central bank will keep the level unchanged this week, according to John Lonski, chief economic expert at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group cluster.
"It will be surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now," he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, "they will have to go to great lengths in their policy statement to support financial markets so that they don't panic."
Other experts argue that the elevated level would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the central bank will act.
Just a month ago, it appeared that the Federal Reserve would be on track to raise interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step toward a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would certify the stability of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen has noted in the spring and early summer that she expects the level to rise this year despite liberal calls for more economic development in her complaints.
Although new job creation slowed in August, labor market growth has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest rate in seven years and close to the level the central bank considers the limit for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of picking up.
Although inflation is still below the central bank's 2 percent annual target, the main reason for this, according to central bank policymakers, is the temporary effect of significantly lowered oil prices.
The economy "is coping with higher interest rates and also needs them given the tight situation in the labour market," notes Ian Shepherdson, chief economic expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16 percent from its May record high as investors feared China's slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10 percent below its May peak.
For central bank policymakers, market turmoil is an additional factor in the complex equation of when to raise interest rates.
"Without these financial market events and the news coverage in recent weeks about the weakness of the Chinese economy, policymakers would be tightening the level at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a special investigator at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate, as well as a former central bank official.
Now, he predicts, policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the impact.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still quite unclear and they don't have much data at their disposal, in terms of the consequences of what's happening in China," Oliner notes.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank's main concern, so in principle it should not influence decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been immense.
In 2013, the implication by the chairman at the time, Ben S. Bernanke, that the central bank can "narrow" monetary expansion caused upheaval in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interwoven, central bank officials are expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to get a better sense of the global economy.
The central bank's decision-making process is "more art than science," notes Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at asset management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, pointed out this month that "the central bank has in the past overreacted to financial market momentum that has appeared to be separate from economic fundamentals."
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for a rate hike, and Lacker, a voting member of the committee, invokes the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian financial crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings "despite its limited, identifiable impact on US economic growth," says Lacker.
A year later, the central bank reversed those cuts.
The central bank should only give priority to financial stability during a major crisis, such as when markets collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's rate-setting committee.
The latest turmoil doesn't come close to its level, Posen notes.
"Nobody wants to be in a situation where there is a fear of raising interest rates because markets are annoyed," Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics, said.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a double requirement and does not mention financial stability. As long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
