Slimming surgery may help mildly obese diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last for at least five years.
However, it is still too early to tell whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are treated in ways other than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get mortality data," Dr. Robin Blackstone notes. She is a weight loss surgery expert who wrote an editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the individuals in the study have been morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
A BMI, or weight to height ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If the BMI is more than 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if the BMI is more than 30, the person is considered obese.
You can calculate your own BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass as well as gastric reduction, with medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of those cut fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
Meanwhile, the BMI of individuals treated with means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Thirty-six percent of the individuals who underwent surgery had a complete cure for diabetes and 28 percent had a partial cure.
In comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes was completely cured in just 1 percent and partially cured in about 2 percent.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, as well as the "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgery group," the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored the patients' blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels over the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c levels should remain below 7 percent, the researchers wrote.
Postoperative hemoglobin A1c levels dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the medical treatment group, it remained stable at about 8 percent.
However, this better "glycemic control," described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, says principal investigator Dr Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The team also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, when compared to the group that underwent gastric reduction surgery, the group that underwent gastric bypass had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), lowered their body mass index more (7.4 and 5.1), lowered their hemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 percent and 2.1 percent), and was more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9 percent and 16.7 percent, respectively).
Blackstone, of the University of Arizona's College of Medicine-Phoenix, says that while the study shows no survival or surgery after five years, there are study results from Sweden, where surgery led to longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who underwent weight loss surgery were 29 per cent less likely to die over a 15-year period when compared to a group who had tried more traditional treatments.
Although the new study shows no improvement in survival among surgical patients, Blackstone says the results are nonetheless encouraging for individuals with a BMI of less than 35 who are interested in surgery.
"The study results are crucial precisely in that they show that surgery is safe for the lower body mass index group" and is not associated with an increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously at the point when the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we're waiting too long before we take this seriously," he says.
I believe that once a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare their body for obesity and diabetes, it will be very tricky to reverse the situation.
