According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Information Center, cases of disinfectant ingestion reported to poison information centers in children under 12 rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16117 in 2014.
"Kids are getting interested in these products more often and, unfortunately, a certain percentage of them are going to be on call," Lopez told CNN.
She said some children drink disinfectant on purpose, while some want to impress their friends or rise to the challenge on social media.
There are videos on YouTube of teenagers drinking disinfectant to get a cheap up-and-coming binge.
According to reports, the teens have mixed disinfectant with an alcoholic mouthwash to get a stronger drink.
Pleasant scents of disinfectant can attract younger children.
"The kid doesn't think this is bad for him," Lopez said.
Many of the more interesting (hand sanitizers) are ones with added fragrance.
There are strawberry, grape and orange-scented disinfectants that are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitizer can contain alcohol of anything between 45 and 95 percent.
Especially in young children, only a few squirts are needed for alcohol poisoning.
"It's really condensed alcohol," Mr. Stephen Thornton, director of medical care at the Poison Information Center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So you wouldn't leave a whiskey shot lying on the table, but hand sanitizer is left in plain sight, and if kids take an interest in it, it's a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell is a six-year-old girl who recently swallowed just four squirts of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, and was taken to the emergency room for treatment.
His blood-alcohol level was .179, which is twice the adult drink-drive limit, according to Chris Ritchey, an emergency room physician who treated the girl at Gwinnet Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah mossed as she spoke and was unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital for possible brain injury symptoms, as alcohol caused the girl to fall and hit her head, Ritchey reported.
"It was really scary," Nhaijah's mother, Ortoria Scott, told CNN.
The situation could have been deadly for my child.
Lopez has recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic products or disinfectant wipes, as well as moving disinfectant out of reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after swallowing hand sanitizer containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials hypothesize that the product contained methanol, a deadly substance, and not ethyl alcohol, which had been reported as an active ingredient.
In January, three fourth graders in upstate New York planned to poison their "nasty" teacher by spreading a bacterial toxin in a classroom, according to a police report.
