FriendsFest: the comedy show that taught us serious things about friendship between men
It's eye-popping how similar portrayals don't exist in shows, particularly given that the need for men to open up is more desperate than ever, and the suicide rate among young men higher than it has been in fifteen years.
In 2013, suicide was the biggest cause of death in men aged 20 to 45 in Britain, and is three times more common in men than women.
In an attempt to tackle the problem, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) announced 2015 as the year for men. The goal was to challenge a culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 students in secondary school and high school showed depressive symptoms. According to the study, a person's chance of recovery doubled if a high enough percentage of their friends were in "healthy spirits."
Similarly, for those who were not depressed, the likelihood of developing possible mental health problems was halved if they had mentally healthy friends.
But for a friendship to work, it has to be available first.
In this time of communicating via social media, style goes by content and the immediacy of the response is often more important than meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled down on the need to appear strong, cheerful and successful, when in reality isolation rules.
This superficial success is dominated by values that psychologists call external: money, image, social status. All of this comes at the expense of internal values - inner yearning for personal growth and friendship - that have a deeper impact on our mental health.
And as the billionaire video game developer explained recently, money really doesn't get you any greater happiness.
The great thing about Friends was that it turned this focus on its head.
None of the characters were defined by their work, but rather by their personalities, which clearly stood out in their interactions as friends.
Joey and Chandler's numerous hugs, their moments in comfortable chairs watching football, Ross missing Rachel - their humour came from the knowledge that, yes, men can relate to all this, even if they are often hesitant to fully explore their feelings.
As a Samaritans volunteer explained to me: ..." listening to people who are depressed and suicidal, I've really understood how even the slightest interaction with a friend can make you feel better."
Often men who contact us feel they can't talk to friends.
The old idea of "getting over" is strong, as is the feeling that if you open up about problems, you'll be seen as weak.
Friends is one of those shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term coping methods.
It highlighted the small moments of friendship between the two men.
While my unbiased, outsider status on the other end of the phone helps people in moments of despair, long-term support comes from a close, personal network of family and friends.
And so if you're attending Comedy Central's FriendsFest this weekend, and all the filming locations have been redesigned to celebrate, why not take your friends for coffee in Central Perk.
Or, better yet, if you see someone lonely at Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know how much your friendship can mean.
