Angel Di Maria scored on his Champions League debut, helping PSG overtake Swedish team Malmo on Tuesday.
Below is the match report and reactions to the game.
Angel Di Maria and Edinson Cavani were on the right line as Paris Saint-Germain finally started their Champions League game with a comfortable 2-0 win against Malmo at the Parc des Princes on Tuesday.
Di Maria scored less than four minutes into his Champions League debut, pointing the way for the French league champions, but the team wasted several chances before finally adding to their advantage as Cavani struck with a goal in the 61st minute.
Paris, who are in the same Group A as Real Madrid and Shakhtar Donetsk, needed a strong start against the Swedish league champion as there was not only a further place to play, but also an improvement in their quarter-final-leading games in the final three rounds
But while PSG took the points, it was no classic game, with Laurent Blanc's team's Zlatan Ibrahimovic losing a place in front of goal and later being substituted from the field. Malmo are his old hometown team and the team he started his brilliant career with in 1999.
"In the Champions League, it's not easy to win at home or away, so a 2-0 win spells trouble for the opponent and looks good in the stats, and is a good start, although there are things we'll have to hone in on this season," Blanc said.
This bodes well.
We wanted to win and we won, although I regret we didn't manage to score one or two more goals.
Ibrahimovic returned to the Parisian team from injury in one of three changes made after the team missed a 2-2 draw in a Ligue 1 home game against Bordeaux at the weekend, but he was overshadowed by Di Maria in the fourth minute.
When he moved from Manchester United last month, the Argentinian winger was named as the man to take PSG to a new level in Europe, and he proved why when he ran onto Marco Verratti's pass behind Malmo's defensive line and then struck a beautiful finish past Johan Wiland into the back corner of the net.
However, if anyone expected an easy and big win from PSG, they were disappointed.
Malmö was a stuffy opponent. It beat Celtic in the deciding game to reach this level, its opening field featuring nine international players and a five-man defence, as well as two players deep in midfield.
But the team offered little on the offensive side other than Nikola Djurdjic's shot in the 34th minute that went nip past Kevin Trapp's goalpost.
Instead, PSG found themselves in a quandary at times because of missed passes and poor finishing from Ibrahimovic in particular, who failed to score five tries in all in the first half alone and was then disappointed when Cavani put the ball in from Ibrahimovic's touch right at the start of the second half.
But he was far more effective in doing some pre-work for his colleagues, and it was from Ibrahimovic's pass that Di Maria sent a twisting kick on its way that tipped around Wiland's goalpost on the 52nd minute.
The second goal was finally scored an hour into the game thanks to Cavani, the Uruguayan who struck his sixth goal of the season after Ibrahimovic had scuffed forward Maxwell's cross pass from the left.
That was the end of Malmo's hopes of getting back into the game, and only Wiland's superb save from David Luiz's direct kick kept the closing numbers down, before substitute Ezequiel Lavezzi's goal was disallowed at the very end of the game.
Malmo coach Age Hareide later admitted PSG were one level above his team. The Norwegian said: "Our last Champions League game was in December last year."
Since then we have only played in the Swedish league, which is not at the same level.
Qualifying matches are not enough.
I take my hat off to Paris.
This was a great game from them.
Glencore to raise $2.5bn through share sale
Glencore, the Swiss-based mining giant hit by the commodity price crash, raised $2.5bn on Wednesday by selling shares as part of its sweeping debt-cutting plan.
Glencore, which is listed on the London Stock Exchange, said in a service note that it had sold new shares worth about £1.6bn to reduce its debt.
The company, which lost 57 percent of its market value this year, is struggling with plummeting commodity prices as China's economic slowdown strains demand and wreaks havoc across all markets.
The new entry put the value of Glencore's shares at the top of the London Stock Exchange in early morning trades on Wednesday.
Shares rose 2.77 percent to 131.60 pence on the FTSE 100 index, which opened 0.69 percent higher.
Glencore had unveiled a $2.5bn share sale the previous week as part of its wider plan to cut its $30bn debt burden by about a third.
The company sold new share capital at 125 pence a share, which meant a 2.4 per cent discount to Tuesday's closing price.
The company sold 1.3 billion shares worth a total of 9.99 percent of the group.
Worries about a long-running standstill in Chinese growth have cut iron ore prices by about half, while coal, copper and other commodity prices have fallen by 20-40 per cent.
White House confirms Xi Jinping visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the United States at the end of the month, a White House statement released Tuesday confirmed.
Xi's first official visit to Washington will take place on September 25 and will be in response to President Barack Obama's recent November visit to Beijing, the statement said.
The US president and First Lady Michelle Obama will host a dinner for Xi and his spouse Peng Liyuan after the leaders hold bilateral talks.
"Prient Xi's visit will provide an opportunity to expand U.S.-China cooperation on numerous global, regional and bilateral issues of mutual interest, and at the same time will allow President Obama and President Xi to constructively discuss issues where there are differences," the statement added.
In the visit, which was first announced in February, Xi is also expected to make an outlier in Seattle on his way to Washington to meet with numerous U.S. technology leaders, before continuing toward New York City and the U.N. General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to discuss a host of contentious topics, including Washington's concerns about China's alleged cyber espionage and the country's increased absolutism in the disputed waters of the South China Sea.
Matt Damon downplays differences in filmmaking
Matt Damon clashed with African-American filmmaker Effie Brown as they discussed the difference Damon says is not needed behind the scenes.
On Sunday night's episode of Project Greenlight, Brown was interrupted by an experienced actor who emphasized the need for different perspectives on the dark-skinned protagonist of the script.
"When we talk about diversity, it's taken into account when choosing actors for a film, not a series," Damon argued.
A shocked Brown reacted with aggrieved disbelief, commenting "Oops! Wow. Okay," while The Martian actor's comments were left hanging in the air.
Other producers Ben Affleck and the Farrelly brothers joined Damon and Brown to discuss the show's finalists.
"I want to urge people to think, whoever the director is, about how they treat Harmony's character," Brown said at the start.
The only dark character is a hooker who is punched by his white pimp.
The producer of The Dear White People claimed the rights to direct the film for finalists Leo Angelos and Kristen Brancaccio; Damon responded harshly that their direction "could end up giving us something we don't want."
After the conversation aired, social media exploded to disapprove of Damon's comments.
Twitter user MrPooni expressed his anger at the film clip, writing: "Matt Damon talking over the only black person in the room and explaining to him the difference is SO WHITE it hurts."
The tweet garnered more than 5000 retweets and 4000 likes since its release.
Damon's comments coincide with a time when accurate racial representation in the media is at the forefront of social discourse.
Following the 2014 killing of teenager Michael Brown by a white police officer, The Black Lives Matter movement sprawled nationwide and called on lawmakers and authorities to end practices that discriminate against people of color.
In February, singer Prince referenced the movement when introducing the Album of the Year nominees for the Grammy Award.
"Albums still matter," he said.
Like books and black lives, albums still matter.
Leaders of the Black Lives Matter movement recently released a statement to answer a question from Fox News television face Elisabeth Hasselbeck about whether the group should be considered a hate group.
"The Black Lives Matter Network is a love group," the executives said.
It was recently reported that Damon is among the entertainers, producers and media moguls invited to visit the pope to discuss the Catholic Church's image in the West.
It is unclear whether he has accepted the invitation or already met with the pope.
First American Ninja Warrior champion crowned
Professional rock climber and crockery collector Isaac Caldiero on Monday became the first athlete to win the American Ninja Warrior competition and was rewarded with a $1 million grand prize.
Just finishing its seventh season, the competition program has never had a contestant survive all sections of the program's obstacle course.
In the show's final episode, two men, Caldiero as well as cameraman Geoff Britten, made it to the final round.
On the last mission, you had to climb a rope of about 23 metres in 30 seconds.
Britten climbed first and cleared the challenge on time, making him the first athlete ever to clear the grueling 4th leg of American Ninja Warrior. But Caldiero cleared the challenge three seconds faster, making him the winner.
Caldiero gave an interview to E!News after the tricky win and was still in shock about winning the $1 million grand prize.
"So it's awesome to think about this, having never made or lived more than $10,000 a year," Isaac told E! after his big pay raise.
So all of a sudden...I can't even imagine what this is going to be...the future is unknown.
Production director Kent Weed sat down with The Hollywood Reporter to discuss the finale and why Britten isn’t getting more reward money, despite being the first contestant ever to break through.
According to the rules, the money goes to the fastest person.
"If more than one person passes, the money will go to whoever has the fastest time," Weed said.
Even though money is a great reward and changes lives, he still gets a great sense of satisfaction.
I don't think he feels bad about it.
He's just so happy that he's been able to do what he did.
His fans have praised him.
He's a great guy and a decent family man.
He is a hero to his children and his wife.
Geoff said to me, 'If anyone had to beat me, I'm happy that it was Isaac.'
And I think Isaac would have felt the same way if this had gone the other way.
"American Ninja Warrior" will return for season eight, which will begin filming in the spring of 2016.
