Xi urges wider opening of economy to world
The economy must open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group Tuesday tasked with steering reform.
"China should commit to attracting foreign funding and expertise and develop a transparency policy," he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the group leading the push for deeper universal reform.
Supporting transparency at the same time as pushing ahead with reforms will add new movement and vitality, as well as create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The executive approved a series of guidelines including a negative list restricting market access, loosening border control principles, urging state-owned enterprises to seize private capital, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the statement, a negative list will be created to name the sectors and companies that are not allowed to invest.
The system is gradually being tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is notable for giving the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a law-based corporate environment and making markets more transparent, the statement said.
The government is also loosening its control over the power it hands out to businesses, thereby ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to run their businesses.
The statement also said China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation as well as new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
More sectors are opening up to private financiers to open up government-controlled sectors.
"The government will not change its policy regarding foreign investment, and it will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies as well as providing them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent resident permits for foreigners, known as "green cards", is facilitated by optimising requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed the guarantee of professional rights for lawyers and support for professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, it said in a statement released after the meeting.
